      "explanation": "This is the balanced budget multiplier theorem. The spending multiplier = 1/(1-MPC) = 1/0.2 = 5, so $50B × 5 = $250B increase. The tax multiplier = -MPC/(1-MPC) = -0.8/0.2 = -4, so $50B × (-4) = -$200B decrease. Net effect: $250B - $200B = +$50B. The balanced budget multiplier always equals 1 regardless of the MPC, meaning an equal increase in G and T raises GDP by exactly the amount of the spending increase. (A) incorrectly ignores the tax effect entirely. (B) is a common misconception that equal changes fully cancel. (D) incorrectly claims the tax multiplier dominates. (E) applies only the spending multiplier and ignores the tax multiplier's negative effect.",
