      "id": "pt_macro_p1_u3_023",
      "unit": 3,
      "question": "A country is experiencing a recessionary gap. Congress passes a $200 billion tax cut (not a spending increase) while the MPC is 0.75. A senator argues this policy will have a smaller stimulative effect than an equivalent $200 billion increase in government spending. Which of the following best evaluates the senator's claim and identifies a potential limitation of this fiscal policy?",
      "choices": [
        "A) The senator is correct; the tax cut multiplier (MPC / MPS = 3) is smaller than the spending multiplier (1 / MPS = 4), because households save a portion of the tax cut rather than spending it all, and the effect may be further diminished if households expect the cut to be temporary.",
        "B) The senator is incorrect; a tax cut directly injects money into consumer spending without any leakage, making it more powerful than government spending, which is subject to bureaucratic delays.",
        "C) The senator is correct; the tax cut multiplier equals the spending multiplier minus one, and the limitation is that tax cuts always increase the budget deficit without any productive output.",
        "D) The senator is incorrect; because MPC = 0.75, the tax multiplier (3) equals the spending multiplier (4), so both policies have identical effects on real GDP.",
        "E) The senator is correct; however, the limitation of government spending is that it crowds out private investment, whereas the tax cut does not affect interest rates at all."
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "The senator is correct. The spending multiplier = 1/MPS = 1/0.25 = 4, so $200B × 4 = $800B increase in GDP. The tax cut multiplier = MPC/MPS = 0.75/0.25 = 3, so $200B × 3 = $600B increase in GDP. The spending multiplier is larger because government spending directly enters GDP as autonomous expenditure, while a tax cut first becomes household income, of which only the MPC fraction (75%) is spent - the rest is saved (the first-round leakage). A key limitation is the Ricardian equivalence concern: if households believe the cut is temporary and will require future tax increases, they may save the entire amount, reducing the actual multiplier toward zero. Choice B is incorrect - tax cuts do have leakage because the MPS fraction is saved rather than spent. Choice C is incorrect for two reasons: while the senator's conclusion is right, this choice undermines the analysis by falsely claiming that tax cuts produce 'no productive output' - tax cuts increase disposable income and do stimulate consumer spending and real GDP; the claim of zero productive output is a misconception that misrepresents how tax-cut stimulus works. Choice D is incorrect because it falsely claims the two multipliers are equal when in fact the spending multiplier (4) exceeds the tax cut multiplier (3). Choice E is incorrect because it evaluates the wrong policy - it critiques government spending rather than identifying a limitation of the tax cut - and it incorrectly asserts that the tax cut has no effect on interest rates; since the question does not specify how the tax cut is financed, one cannot assume it is deficit-neutral, and even if deficit-financed, claiming zero interest rate effect is unsupported.",
