      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "The standard monetary transmission mechanism for expansionary policy: The Fed increases the money supply (e.g., via open market purchases) → in the money market, supply of money shifts right, lowering the nominal interest rate → lower interest rates reduce the cost of borrowing, increasing investment spending (and other interest-sensitive spending) → the increase in investment shifts aggregate demand rightward → real GDP increases toward potential. Choice A has the interest rate effect backwards - an increase in money supply lowers, not raises, interest rates. Choice C describes a decrease in money supply, which is contractionary. Choice D correctly shows falling interest rates but then wrongly states investment decreases. Choice E is mechanically accurate in its description of the bond market channel (when the Fed buys bonds, bond demand increases, bond prices rise, and yields fall), but it is a distractor because the question specifically asks about the money market framework, making Choice B the cleaner and more directly applicable answer. Students familiar with the bond market transmission mechanism may find Choice E appealing, but Choice B more precisely reflects the money market model referenced in the question.",
