      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "When the central bank purchases government bonds (expansionary open market operations), it injects reserves into the banking system, increasing the money supply. With more money available, interest rates fall, which reduces the cost of borrowing and stimulates investment and consumption, shifting aggregate demand to the right. Choice A describes contractionary policy (selling bonds). Choice C incorrectly pairs an increased money supply with rising interest rates-these move inversely. Choice D describes selling bonds (contractionary). Choice E misunderstands the mechanism: bond purchases increase the money supply, and lower interest rates (not just lower bond prices in isolation) drive investment increases.",
