      "explanation": "A negative supply shock shifts the short-run Phillips curve outward (stagflation: higher inflation and higher unemployment simultaneously). When the central bank expands the money supply in response, it does not fix the underlying supply shock-the SRPC has already shifted outward. The expansionary policy moves the economy along this new, less favorable SRPC, reducing unemployment but at the cost of even higher inflation (above the post-shock 6%). Choice A incorrectly assumes the economy returns to the original SRPC, ignoring the shift. Choice B describes an impossible simultaneous improvement without addressing the supply shock. Choice C places the movement on the original curve, which no longer applies. Choice E is incorrect because the long-run Phillips curve is vertical at the natural rate of unemployment, which is determined by structural and frictional factors. Expansionary monetary policy cannot shift the LRPC left or permanently lower the natural rate.",
